              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong>              <strong> <a href="http://news.com.com/2100-7344_3-5701861.html">India eyes own open-source license</a></strong> <br>
              CNETnews.com, May 11, 2005 --</strong> Deepak Phatak of the Indian Institute of Technology has kicked off an effort to create the Knowledge Public License, or KPL, a licensing program that will let programmers share ideas with one another while at the same time allowing them to retain the rights to their own software modifications. The license will likely function much like the Berkeley Software Distribution or the MIT License programs, he added. The idea is to create an environment where developers can take advantage of the collaborative power of the open-source movement while giving individuals the ability to exploit their own twists. Ideally, such a program could also help ease the raging tensions between the open-source software movement and proprietary software companies. ...<a href="http://news.com.com/2100-7344_3-5701861.html">Full Story </a></p>
