              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong> <span class="style2"><a href="http://www.niso.org/news/newsline/NISONewsline-May2005.html#Story1">OpenURL Now a National Standard </a><br>
              </span></strong><strong>NISO Press Release, May 4, 2005 --</strong> The OpenURL Framework for Context-Sensitive Services (ANSI/NISO Z39.88-2004), which defines an architecture for creating a context-sensitive networked service environment, has received approval as an American National Standard. The standard had been in trial use since June 2003 and is now deployed in Google Scholar The OpenURL standard allows for the emergence of many different web-based service environments in which the context of the user is taken into account. For example, if the OpenURL is used in a service environment supporting the scholarly information community, a researcher or student searching for a scholarly information resource can get immediate access to the most appropriate copy of that item. In this case &quot;appropriateness&quot; reflects the user's context, such as location, cost of the item, and the contractual or license agreements in place with the information suppliers the university library does business with. ...<a href="http://www.niso.org/news/newsline/NISONewsline-May2005.html#Story1">Full Story </a></p>
