                      <p class="style79"><strong><em> <strong><em> <strong><em> <strong><em> <strong><em> A billion potential customers focuses the mind:</em></strong></em></strong></em></strong></em></strong></em></strong><em><em><em><em><em> We dedicated our last issue to China, and the many standards-based facets of the emergence of that enormous country as a powerhouse on the world economic stage. Much of the current action involves the roll out of the third generation of cell phone technology &ndash; and who will make the profits from that technology in a market that already owns more cell phones than there are people in the United States. The following selection of articles summarizes the key themes at play: the resentment of China over the disadvantages it has historically suffered at the hands of the countries that already own the key technology patents, the upcoming decision by Beijing over who will get the licenses to roll out the technology (and what that technology will be &ndash; foreign or domestic), concerns in Washington over how standards will be incorporated into China&rsquo;s trade policy, and, finally, the jockeying going on among Chinese and foreign manufacturers that want to be sure that they get a substantial piece of the action, no matter what standards are selected. </em></em></em></em></em></p></td>
